Final post on this, but there is a somewhat unnerving scene in Twin Peaks that follows the same pattern. Major Briggs is taking a walk through the woods when Windom Earle appears wearing a horse costume. It's so out of place that Briggs freezes up staring at him as if hypnotized.

His mind is unable to process what he is seeing and in this state of confusion Windom proceeds to shoot him with a tranquilizer dart making him black out and he wakes up at a different location later. Earle is portrayed as an expert in Eastern occult technique so it does fit.

I remember seeing a random post on the TL years ago by some woman here who said she was an assistant professor at some university and one of her (a lot younger than her) male students had sent her an email admitting that he had fallen in love with her and asking her out on a date

It really struck me how a person can cultivate this air of romanticism and surround themselves with art and poetry and then act so sour and cold when such an organic situation arises instead of handling it with elegance and compassion. We all fail to live up to our stated ideals.

In the tweet she was really scandalized and said how she replied how this was absolutely unprofessional, totally unacceptable, breaks the academic codes of conduct. But checking her entire profile was full of posts about poetry, older novels, art, her taste was even quite decent.
He's definitely risking like a 5% chance of being put in a  GITMO cell one day over 20 dollars of elonbucks

Reminds me of how Fr. De Young said in the original Hebrew in Genesis "Sin is crouching at your door" actually uses an Akkadian word that describes a specific type of crawling demon that comes out at night from cracks in the ground & pounces on people. Every force is personified.
